            <summary>
              <p>Single folio; Shelfmark: KFQ 73; Writing surface: paper; Qurʾānic text: Q 2:282-3:4; Lines per page: 22, Script style: New Style I; Dimensions: 280 x 180 mm. Estimated date of production: 1000-1200. </p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>The catalogue written by François Déroche gives the following information (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">Déroche, The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992, p. 172</ref>): „90 / Single folio / 11th or 12th century AD / 28 x 18cm, with 22 lines to the page / <hi rend="italic">Material</hi> A thin, brittle, buff paper, laid, with 4-5 lines to the centimetre; the lines are parallel to the spine / <hi rend="italic">Text area</hi> 23.3 x 14.5cm / <hi rend="italic">Script</hi> Style NS.I / <hi rend="italic">Accession no.</hi> KFQ 73 / Style NS.I appears here in a form whose simplicity reflects the popularity and wide diffusion of the style. The text – <hi rend="italic">Sūrat al-baqarah </hi>(II), verse 277, to <hi rend="italic">Sūrat </hi><hi rend="italic">āl </hi><hi rend="italic">ʿImr</hi><hi rend="italic">ān</hi> (III), verse 4 – is written in black ink, with diacritical dots and strokes. Red dots indicate the vocalization, while the <hi rend="italic">shaddah</hi>, which has its modern shape, is written in ink. A 3.A.II device in the margin marks the end of a group of ten verses. The title of surah III is written in NS script outlined in ink.“</p>
              <p> Fragment <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/2/vers/185?handschrift=1494">HC.MS.2017.0046</ref> seems to come from the same original manuscript.</p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>Unfortunately only a small selection of images from this manuscripts (as in the catalogue <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ">Abbasid Tradition</ref>, p. 173) are on display in this catalogue.</p>
            </summary>
